To generate a table of contents automatically in a LATEX document, you can use the `tableofcontents` package. Here's an example:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tableofcontents}

\title{My Document}
\author{}
\date{}
\begin{document}

\maketoc

\tableofcontents

\maintext

\chapter{Introduction}

\section{Section 1.1}
\subsection{Subsection 1.1.1}
\subsubsection{Subsection 1.1.1.1}

\section{Section 2}

\chapter{Conclusion}

\end{document}
```

In this example, the `\maketoc` command generates the table of contents directly after the `\title`, `\author`, and `\date` commands. The `\tableofcontents` command generates the actual table of contents, while `\maintext` and `\chapter` commands are for controlling the flow of the document.

When you compile this file using a LATEX compiler and the `tableofcontents` package is installed, it will automatically generate the table of contents. You can also customize the appearance of the table of contents using various options provided by the package.

Make sure to compile the file using a LATEX compiler like pdflatex or xetex to see the automatically generated table of contents.

