To solve this problem without using loops or recursion, we can take advantage of the fact that 3^2 = 9 and 3^3 = 27. Since 27 is given as an example, we can conclude that if n is a power of three, then n must be divisible by 9.

Here is a Java solution that uses this observation to determine if n is a power of three:

```java
public class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        return n > 0 && n % 9 == 0;
    }
}
```

In this solution, we check if n is greater than 0 and if it is divisible by 9. If both conditions are true, then n is a power of three. Otherwise, it is not.

This solution has a time complexity of O(1) because it only performs a single arithmetic operation (integer division) to check if n is divisible by 9.

